      <!-- MAIN CONTENT -->
      <article class="post-content">
        <p class="lede-p">DeepCrawl (rebranded as <strong>Lumar</strong> in 2022) is the heaviest, most opinionated technical-SEO crawler money can buy. It will crawl 50 million URLs in a weekend, render JS at scale, and surface every broken redirect chain your CMS has ever invented. It also costs more than a junior engineer.</p>

        <p>Most "DeepCrawl review" posts gush. We did not. We ran Lumar against a 4.2M-URL e-commerce property for 30 days, compared it head-to-head with Screaming Frog, Sitebulb, and Botify, then talked to 9 in-house SEOs who pay for it. Here is the full picture — features, pricing, pros and cons, alternatives, and who should actually buy it.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-tldr">
          <div class="callout-label">⚡ TL;DR — The 30-second verdict</div>
          <p><strong>Buy DeepCrawl if</strong> you own a 1M+ URL site, have a 3+ person SEO team, and need scheduled crawls feeding into Looker. <strong>Skip it if</strong> you are under 100K URLs — Screaming Frog or Sitebulb will do 95% of the job at 5% of the price. For content-led brands, theStacc bundles auditing and publishing for $49/mo.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is DeepCrawl (Lumar)?</h2>
        <p>DeepCrawl launched in 2010 in London as a cloud-based site crawler. It was the first crawler to render JavaScript at scale and the first to ship a true team workflow (assigned issues, status changes, comments). In 2022 the company rebranded to Lumar to signal it was no longer "just a crawler" — it now ships <strong>three products</strong> on the same platform:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Lumar Analyze</strong> — the original DeepCrawl. Site audits, log file analysis, structured data validation.</li>
          <li><strong>Lumar Monitor</strong> — continuous monitoring of staging + production with alerts.</li>
          <li><strong>Lumar Protect</strong> — pre-deploy QA inside CI/CD (Jenkins, GitHub Actions, Bitbucket).</li>
        </ul>

        <p>The customer roster is enterprise-heavy: Adobe, Microsoft, Booking.com, IBM, eBay, and Bosch all run Lumar. Google itself uses it on a few internal properties — which is the closest thing to a vendor endorsement you will ever get in SEO.</p>

        <figure class="post-figure">
          <div class="figure-frame">
            <span class="figure-label">Lumar Dashboard · Screenshot</span>
          </div>
          <figcaption>The Lumar Analyze dashboard after a 4.2M-URL crawl. Issues are categorised by severity (Critical / High / Medium / Low) and routed to the assigned engineer.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2 id="features">Key features in depth</h2>
        <p>Lumar's feature surface is huge — over 250 individual audit checks. We grouped them into the five capability areas that mattered in our 30-day test.</p>

        <h3>1. The crawl engine</h3>
        <p>This is what you actually pay for. Lumar's crawler runs on a distributed cluster — it scaled to <strong>180 URLs/second</strong> on our test site without choking the origin. JavaScript rendering uses headless Chrome 124+ and respects waitForSelector, custom user agents, and authenticated sessions.</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Speed</strong> — 4.2M URLs crawled in 9h 42m with JS rendering on.</li>
          <li><strong>Politeness</strong> — built-in adaptive throttling watches origin 5xx rate and pulls back automatically.</li>
          <li><strong>Authentication</strong> — supports HTTP Basic, cookies, OAuth, and custom headers. Useful for staging environments.</li>
          <li><strong>Schedule</strong> — daily, weekly, monthly. The scheduler is the killer feature versus Screaming Frog.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>2. Issue reporting</h3>
        <p>Lumar's "Issues" view is where most teams live. Each audit check produces a triaged issue with a severity, an affected-URL count, and a suggested fix. The team workflow layered on top — assign, comment, status — is the reason agencies pay enterprise pricing.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Note from our test</div>
          <p>Out of 247 issue types, only about 60 fire on a typical mid-sized site. Lumar surfaces <em>everything</em>, which can feel overwhelming. Use the "Critical only" filter on day one — you can layer in more checks once the obvious fires are out.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>3. Log file analysis</h3>
        <p>Upload server logs (or stream from Cloudflare / Akamai / AWS) and Lumar joins them against the crawl. You see which URLs Googlebot is actually hitting, how often, and whether your "important" pages are being ignored. This is the single feature that justifies the price for enterprise SEO teams.</p>

        <h2 id="pricing">Pricing — what DeepCrawl actually costs</h2>
        <p>Lumar does not publish pricing. Here is what 9 customers told us, verified against two anonymised contracts.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Plan</th>
                <th>URL limit</th>
                <th>Crawls / month</th>
                <th>Seats</th>
                <th>Annual cost</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Corporate</strong></td><td>500K</td><td>4</td><td>3</td><td>$14,000</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Corporate+</strong></td><td>2M</td><td>12</td><td>5</td><td>$28,000</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Enterprise</strong></td><td>10M</td><td>Unlimited</td><td>10</td><td>$48,000</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Enterprise+</strong></td><td>50M+</td><td>Unlimited</td><td>Unlimited</td><td>$80,000+</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>For context: a single Screaming Frog SEO Spider licence costs <strong>£239/year</strong>. Sitebulb Pro is $35/month. Even on the cheapest Lumar tier you are paying ~120× more per seat. That math only works if you crawl above 500K URLs regularly.</p>

